        <span>Servings / person / year</span>
      </div>
      <div id="region-bar-chart"></div>
    </div>
    <div>
      <p style="font-size:15px;color:var(--muted);line-height:1.8;margin-bottom:24px">
        <strong style="color:var(--text)">The European Exception.</strong> Europe is the only region where wine holds comparable weight to beer and spirits. Countries like France (370 wine servings), Portugal (339), and Slovenia (276) drive the average up dramatically.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:15px;color:var(--muted);line-height:1.8;margin-bottom:24px">
        <strong style="color:var(--text)">The African Surprise.</strong> Sub-Saharan Africa out-drinks Asia. Countries like Gabon (347 beer), Namibia (376 beer), and Nigeria (9.1L total) push the continent's average higher than many expect — despite strong Islamic influence in North Africa pulling the average down.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:15px;color:var(--muted);line-height:1.8">
        <strong style="color:var(--text)">The Caribbean Paradox.</strong> Small island nations — Grenada, Haiti, St. Lucia — rank among the world's heaviest drinkers. Rum and sugarcane spirit production shapes local consumption patterns profoundly.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

